<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Lorraine Wapling</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Lorraine Wapling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, Disability Inclusive Development Consultant</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: I am a trained teacher by profession with 18 years experience working in international development; my particular focus is on disability inclusion; I have conducted research, managed projects working with disabled people, designed training for disability inclusion, and evaluated a range of disability inclusive programs for INGOs and government agencies across Africa, Asia and the Pacific; I spent two years as the Disability Specialist for DFID in their Policy and Research Division and was the Disability Specialist for the 2012 Mid Term review of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Development for All</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> disability inclusive development strategy. I am profoundly deaf.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In this submission, I will address the following:</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Disability as a development issue.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The mandate provided by the UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Learning from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Development for All</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> disability inclusive development strategy.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Disability is present in all communities, cuts across all sectors and affects every generation regardless of gender, ethnicity, or class. This reason alone makes it a compellingly relevant issue in development. With</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> over </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">one billion persons with disabilities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in the world, of whom between 110</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-190 million </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">experience impairments that have a direct impact on their life choices </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(WHO, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, it might be anticipated that disability would feature in many development programs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Yet with exceptions, disability hardly features at all in the work of international agencies. Some reports suggest as little as 3-4% of global development directly benefits disabled people (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2011). Its absence from international frameworks like the Millennium Development Goals means not only have disabled people failed to benefit from much of the recent progress brought about by their focus but there is growing concern that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> living conditions may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">actually </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">declining in relative terms </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(UN, 2010)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. With the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">prevalence of disability growing </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">due to population ageing and the global increase in chronic health conditions (WHO, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the issue of disability and its impact on development outcomes will increase in significance. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There is a significant </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">link between poverty and disability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, especially chronic poverty </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mitra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Posarac</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, &amp; Vick, 2011).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> There is a significant risk of becoming disabled if you are poor because of the conditions in which you live. You are less likely to be able to access timely and appropriate health care, you are more vulnerable to malnutrition and disease, and more likely to live in low quality housing with poor sanitation, in areas that are at higher risk of natural disaster, environmental damage and violence (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Groce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, 2011).  Those with a disability are more likely to experience poverty more intensely. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Households with disabled members have considerably </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reduced economic resilience and can be subject to repeated economic shocks from a lack of access to the goods and services they need. Many disabled people face constraints over ownership of land, assets </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and access to credit due to attitudinal and environmental barriers. Since many are denied the opportunity to take part in political processes by these same barriers, they also lack the voice to challenge the situation (ILO, 2013). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The cost of living with a disability may also contribute to increased household poverty</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> meaning disability affects not just individuals but also their families and communities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Disability can reduce an individual’s opportunity to earn a sufficient income but that may be compounded by a need for increased spending linked to their disability. Households that contain a disabled member may have to spend more in order to rea</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ch a minimum standard of living</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his extra level of expenditure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">means that where there are few or no state supported disability services, households with disabled members are at an increased risk of falling into poverty (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mitra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> et al, 2011). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">economic benefits of disability inclusive development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are starting to become clearer although this is an area that needs more focused research. It is reasonably well established that constructing physically accessible infrastructure adds only 1-2% to the overall costs if built in from the start using Universal Design guidelines. But that only accounts for the direct spend, what it doesn’t show is how much is generated from having increased numbers of disabled people active in the economy. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">With at least </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">780 million disabled people of working age</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in the world today there is considerable economic potential. However, we consistently find that disabled people are excluded from the workforce and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">in addition</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are dependent on their families for support. Around the world </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">disabled people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> more likely to be unemployed than non-disabled people, be lower paid, have fewer promotion prospects and less job security. A lack of education, inaccessible workplaces</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and transport</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">alongside</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> negative attitudes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and discriminatory practices</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">work against </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">who strive to make a living</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (ILO, 2013).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1.6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">If disabled people are given appropriate access to education, social protection, employment and livelihood opportunities they have the potential to play an important role in the economic and social development of their countries. A 2011 study from Australia highlighted that it could experience a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">$43 billion increase in GDP over the next ten years if the gaps between unemployment and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">labour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> market participation of disabled and non-disabled</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> people are reduced by just a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">third (Deloitte, 2011).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> An ILO study of ten low and middle-income countries in Asia and Africa found significant levels of economic loss, ranging from 3-7% of GDP directly related to disability (S. Backup, 2012). Evidence is growing therefore around the extent to which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">improved economic indicators could be gained from investing in disability inclusive development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The landscape within which development agencies now operate has changed considerably since 2008 when the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UN Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> came into force. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This reinforced the paradigm shift that has been taking place in the way disability is framed (driven by the disability movement), away from its medical/charity focus to one based on rights and equality of opportunities. The CRPD intends that members States </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">create positive </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> enabling environment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s both</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> domestically and internationally for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">disabled people.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Governments should focus on identifying and removing the barriers that prevent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">disabled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">people from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">enjoying</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> their rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and fundamental freedoms. In fact the CRPD is unique in being both a human rights and a development tool because it is currently the only rights framework that has a specific article on international cooperation. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Article 32</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> mandates that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">international cooperation ‘…is inclusive of and accessible to persons with disabilities</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.’ This makes it highly relevant to the work of DFID and other bilateral, and multilateral agencies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">UK government ratified the CRPD in 2009</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which give</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> DFID the mandate and the responsibility to build disability into its bilateral </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">aid discussions, humanitarian responses, research and development funding. Although DFID aims to ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">work to end extreme poverty</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(see website)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and targets areas such as education, health, and economic growth it does not as yet have a coherent, time-bound, measurable and resourced strategy for disability inclusive development. As a result, it is not possible to measure the extent to which DFID is able to fulfill this mandate which was highlighted by the poor quality of information on international cooperation presented in the 2011 Initial Report to the UN on the CRPD</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (ODI, 2011)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">My work takes me to many countries in Africa, Asia and the Pacific </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">where</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> I meet with DPOs and those engaged in supporting disability inclusion. I also get to see the work of bilateral agencies, multilaterals and mainstream development </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. What I see on a regular basis is an almost total disconnection between mainstream development and disability. There are very few examples where poverty alleviation, education, WASH, HIV, health or livelihood programs actively include disabled people alongside their non-disabled peers. DFID is not currently making </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">any visible </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">efforts to understand if its mainstream programs are improving the lives of disabled people despite recognizing back in 2000 (when it produced its Disability, Poverty and Development Issues Paper) that “Disability is both a cause and a consequence of poverty”.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DPOs continue to struggle to source longer term development funding because they find it hard to meet the criteria set by donors and because there are very few funding opportunities offered to them.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst the Disability Rights Fund (to which DFID has been contributing since it was established in 2007) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is an excellent source it only works in 24 countries (only 4 of those in Africa) and has limited resources to offer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> individual grantees</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The fact disabled people are often not included in mainstream programs either, means there is very little in the way of opportunity presented to most disabled people from development cooperation. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Learning from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. In 2012 I was one of two consultants hired by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (now Australian Aid) to carry out a Mid-Term Review of their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Development For All</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DfA</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">) disability inclusive development strategy. As a result I have seen at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">first hand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> how a bilateral agency can embed the principles of disability inclusion into their aid program. Whilst the report itself is freely available (</span><a href="http://aid.dfat.gov.au/aidissues/did/Pages/home.aspx"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://aid.dfat.gov.au/aidissues/did/Pages/home.aspx</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">) there are a number of lessons I would like to draw attention to because I feel they are areas which DFID could well benefit from considering.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Strategic level commitments.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Development for All</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">strategy has been a central driver of change within the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. It is a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">clear, measurable, time-bound agency-wide strategy, supported at senior level and overseen by a core Disability Policy Section. Its inception had </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">high level political support – launched by the then Parliamentary Secretary Bob McMullan and publicly supported by the then Minister for Foreign Affairs, Mr. Smith and Prime Minister Rudd. But it maintained its profile with successive Ministers and Prime Ministers publicly supporting and promoting it. It continues to have senior </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> support in Canberra reflected in its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">inclusion in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Top 10 development priorities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ee “Helping the World’s Poor thr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ough Effective Aid: Australia’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Comprehensive Aid Policy Framework to 2015-16”, page 7)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. During the review process I was particularly struck by the number of senior personnel (in fact all personnel I met) who were confident about discussing disability inclusion and were willing to talk about its benefits and challenges.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">process</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of creating this strategy also helped raise the profile of disability inclusive development. They had over 500 written submissions and held consultations in 20 countries which helped to generate considerable interest. In fact it was as a direct result of the consultation process that the Samoa Ministry of Women, Community and Social Development made a request to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to be included as a focus country. The bilateral work that resulted from this initial request has been significant, especially in education.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.4</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Resourcing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The strategy contains three enabling outcomes, two of which focus on what </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> needs to have in place to implement inclusion, with funding allocated to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Policy Section</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (additional funding is also made available across the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for programs that are working on disability inclusion). In recognition of the fact that most of the strategy has to be implemented by country offices (in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, referred to as Posts) there is a network of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Focal Points</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at Posts. These focal points directly engage with DPOs, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and institutions working with disabled people and the relevant government ministries. Although informal at first, the role of focal points was formalized with training and support opportunities made available. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.5</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are also two </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Inclusive Development Specialists</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">based in Asia and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the Pacific with Inclusion O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">fficers </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">placed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Asia and Pacific regional Divisions. So </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">whilst there is a central Disability Policy Section who are able to monitor and promote the strategy the agency benefited from a whole network of personnel working on disability. It was not therefore confined to a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">single thematic area thus encouraging the sense of ownership needed to mainstream disability inclusive development.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> also realized they needed to provide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">good quality</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">technical support</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to Posts and Divisions as their experience in disability was minimal. For this they set up a partnership with CBM Australia, which worked by making resources rapidly available and by strengthening the skills and capacity of a wider group of stakeholders (via CBM-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Nossal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Institute Partnership in Disability, based at The University of Melbourne). This helped to develop the capacity of local universities and DPOs to research key disability issues and gave </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> staff access to important data and technical advice.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.7</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Engagement with disabled people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. One of the most impressive findings from the MTR was the extent to which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> staff, at Post and in Canberra were connected to and engaged with disabled people. The creation of a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disability Reference Group</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (DRG) has been very important. This consultative body is made up of the majority disabled people, who are active in the field of disability inclusive development. It contains several highly regarded disability leaders from around the world and provides </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with a high level of technical advice and support as well as good networking and a legitimacy to their work. Members can be called on to support </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at international and national forums (e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ms Charlotte McClain-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Nhlapo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – Coordinator, Office for Disability and Inclusive Development, USAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mr </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Setareki</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> S. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Macanawai</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – CEO, Pacific Disability Forum</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> both made presentations at </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> side event at the UN’s Conference of States Parties to the CRPD in July 2013)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and it established good links with senior management, Ministers and cross party politicians. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.8</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The strategy contains a clear commitment to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">supporting the participation of disabled people</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">part of which focuses on building the leadership potential of disabled people and DPOs. They have, for example been very supportive of the Pacific Disability Forum (PDF) helping PDF to promote the voice of disabled people at national and international forums. In country, there were many examples of where focal points were in touch with DPOs helping them source potential areas of funding and connecting them to forums and training opportunities. In Fiji for example, this relationship enabled the Fiji </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Disabled People’s Federation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to link with the Red Cross to ensure disabled people are now </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">included in the national disaster framework</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.9</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Increasing the impact of aid.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> There was clear evidence from the review that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> were using innovative approaches to enable the inclusion of disabled people in their activities and therefore increasing the impact of their aid. Mainstreaming is happening in the two focus areas of infrastructure and education. Both established their own policy base in line with the strategy and are increasingly able to demonstrate, through key performance indicators that they are reaching disabled people. This means the disability inclusive mandate extends beyond the strategy itself and has become much more of a shared responsibility. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Mainstreaming is also starting to emerge at Post. There were a number of examples of where programs were adapted to become inclusive – the electoral program in Philippines (“Fully </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Abled</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Nation” implemented by the Asia Foundation and designed to increase participation of disabled people in the 2013 Mid Term elections) and education in PNG (a flagship program which began using the Accessible Design principles to look at how to construct more accessible classrooms). The original program designs did not pay attention to disability issues at all but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> staff were successful in introducing small but strategic changes to increase inclusion.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.11</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The strategy has also played a role in empowering governments to request the support of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to help them implement disability inclusive activities. In PNG for example the government used the strategy to request assistance to help in the CRPD ratification process. Through its </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Democratic Governance Program</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> engaged with the Department for Community Development</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to support its work as Chair of the National Advisory Committee on Disability. This cross-departmental group was tasked with ensuring the government could comply with the CRPD. They achieved ratification this year. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Similarly in Samoa part of their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">bilateral aid agreement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Australia Partnership for Development – Education) contained a target (one of five) on </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Increased access of boys and girls with disabilities to quality education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. The Ministry of Education, Sport and Culture is being supported to create a strategic framework that will ensure the education of disabled children is effectively implemented through mainstream services. To ensure they set up the most appropriate provisions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are supporting a pilot, the Samoa Inclusive Education Demonstration Program (SIEDP), which is generating important evidence for them to work with. This is an example of a highly innovative bilateral relationship.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.13</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Mainstreaming is also happening in areas that were not specifically targeted by the strategy. One particularly impressive example is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">volunteer program</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Australian Volunteers for International Development) which started to mainstream disability because it saw the potential importance. It has since increased its work in the disability sector and hired increasing numbers of disabled volunteers. They also now have a policy which helps embed disability into all aspects of their work.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.14</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> There are other ways in which </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is helping to promote disability inclusive development at the international level. It supported the regional based Pacific Islands Forum Secretariat to hold its first Disabled Ministers’ meeting in 2009 which resulted in the Pacific Regional Strategy on Disability (2010 – 2015). Many Pacific Islands are now signatories or have disability policies. They are highly visible at UN forums and meetings and generate a lot of opportunities to promote the voice of disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.15</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">They are also </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">funding strategic partnerships</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> with a disability focus. UNICEF, WHO and UNDP all have the promotion of disability inclusion as part of their partnership agreements.  UNICEF and WHO have funding to support specific personnel to work on disability inclusion. During interviews with UN partners they welcomed the opportunity that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> stimulates </span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to work on disability and even suggested that stricter targets from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">bilaterals</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> would help them move towards inclusion more quickly. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">3.16</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">DFID needs to be strategic in its approach to disability inclusion, ensure there are sufficient resources available, especially in-country, engage directly with disabled people and pay attention to monitoring the effectiveness of its aid on reaching disabled people.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AusAID</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (2011).</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> Development for All: Achievement Highlight the First two Years.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Canberra, ACT. From</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a href="http://www.ausaid.gov.au/publications/pdf/disabilityachievementhighlights.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.ausaid.gov.au/publications/pdf/disabilityachievementhighlights.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Buckup</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> S. (2009). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The price of exclusion: The economic consequences of excluding people with disabilities from the world of work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, ILO, Geneva</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Deloitte Access Economics (2011). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The economic benefits of increasing employment for people with disability</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, Sydney http://www.deloitte.com/assets/Dcom- Australia/Local%20Assets/Documents/Industries/LSHC/Deloitte_DAE_Report_8May2012.pdf  [accessed 10 October 2013].</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Groce</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> N. (2011). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Disability and the Millennium Development Goals: A review of the MDG process and strategies for inclusion of disability issues in Millennium Development Goal efforts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. UNDESA, UN Publications New York.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ILO (2013). </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Priority Issues and Recommendations f